Income Prediction

Based on Census Data

UCIs Machine Learning Repository, Adult Data Set: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Adult

  • Predicts if income is above or below $50,000 based on census data.
  • Extraction was done by Barry Becker taken from 1994 Census database

Categories of Adult Income Data

age: continuous. workclass: Private, Self-emp-not-inc, Self-emp-inc, Federal-gov, Local-gov, State-gov, Without-pay, Never-worked.

fnlwgt: continuous.

education: Bachelors, Some-college, 11th, HS-grad, Prof-school, Assoc-acdm, Assoc-voc, 9th, 7th-8th, 12th, Masters, 1st-4th, 10th, Doctorate, 5th-6th, Preschool.

education-num: continuous.

marital-status: Married-civ-spouse, Divorced, Never-married, Separated, Widowed, Married-spouse-absent, Married-AF-spouse.

occupation: Tech-support, Craft-repair, Other-service, Sales, Exec-managerial, Prof-specialty, Handlers-cleaners, Machine-op-inspct, Adm-clerical, Farming-fishing, Transport-moving, Priv-house-serv, Protective-serv, Armed-Forces.

relationship: Wife, Own-child, Husband, Not-in-family, Other-relative, Unmarried.

race: White, Asian-Pac-Islander, Amer-Indian-Eskimo, Other, Black.

sex: Female, Male.

Categories of Adult Income Data Continued

capital-gain: continuous

capital-loss: continuous

hours-per-week: continuous.

native-country: United-States, Cambodia, England, Puerto-Rico, Canada, Germany, Outlying-US(Guam-USVI-etc), India, Japan, Greece, South, China, Cuba, Iran, Honduras, Philippines, Italy, Poland, Jamaica, Vietnam, Mexico, Portugal, Ireland, France, Dominican-Republic, Laos, Ecuador, Taiwan, Haiti, Columbia, Hungary, Guatemala, Nicaragua, Scotland, Thailand, Yugoslavia, El-Salvador, Trinadad&Tobago, Peru, Hong, Holand-Netherlands.

Attribute Details

fnlwgt:

The number of people one row represents

marital-status:

Married-civ-spouse: Married to a civilian

Married-AF-spouse: Married to someone in the Armed Forces

Motivation

Help us in our own careers.

See historically what attributes people have to increase wage.

Challenges

Different characters in the name: Married-civ-spouse has a space in the front

Some values are missing in rows

1. How many people are there for each education category?

Analysis

The lowest count is for people who had a completed doctorate degree.

The highest category was for grades 1st-4th - which makes sense for education levels where all individuals above the age of 5 will have at least a base level of educaiton.

2. Does the workclass affect if the individual make above or below 50k a year?

Private Self-emp-not-inc Self-emp-inc Federal-gov Local-gov State-gov Without-pay Never-worked
>50K 4963 724 622 371 617 353 0 0
<=50K 17733 1817 494 589 1476 944 14 7

Barplot

Analysis

Most individuals in private made over $50,000.

The next category that leaned heavily with more people making more than $50,000 were those in self-employed not-incorporated.

However, those who were self-employed and incorporated tended to make less than $50,000.

3. Hours per week vs above or below 50k a year

Analysis

On Average, people that work over 40 hours a week have wages >50k

4. Does making above or below 50k have an impact on marital status?

Married, Civilian Spouse Divorced Never Married Separated Widowed Married, Spouse Absent Married, Armed Forces Spouse
>50K 6692 463 491 66 85 34 10
<=50K 8284 3980 10191 959 908 384 13

Barplot

Analysis

There largest group of people that make over 50k are married.

The largest group of people that make under 50k have never been married.

5. Does gender have an effect on wages?

Analysis

Of all men, 44% of the data has an income over $50,000.

In comparison, only 12.3% of women have an income over $50,000.

Based on population of data, this shows a significant discrepency on gender-pay ratios.

6. Does the hours per week affect relationship and marital status?

Analysis

Based off the bar graph, people married work the most hours.

Widowed individuals seem to have the lowest hours worked per week. This can be due a variety of reasons, most likely due to increased familial obligations.

7. Does occupation and education affect wage?

8. Occupation

Hours per Week by Occupation

Analysis

Farming-fishing had the largest range in hours worked per week.

Most occupations had a mean that steadied around 40 hours/week.
